Title: Is there a mind gene?  
Author: Ajit Narayanan 
Keyword: evolutionary psychology; mentalism; intentionality; adaptationism; biomolecular science.  
Address: Exeter EX4 4PT UK  
Affiliation: Computer and Cognitive Sciences University of Exeter  
Abstract: Recent advances in biomolecular science and gene cloning have significantly increased our understanding of the role and function of human DNA. The question of whether there is an inheritable mind gene (or set of genes for mind) in the human genome can be predicted to become of increasing importance as individual genes are located and their functions identified. The paper identifies possible genetic accounts of the source, structure and content of mind by proposing three fundamental principles of mind gene theory: that different types of mental state stand in a certain relation to larger or smaller regions of the mind gene set; that mind emerges or results from DNA-based intra and interneuronal activity; and that cognitive states produced by DNA are intentional in virtue of mind genes. Recent DNA-based experimental models of behavioural and cognitive processes are cited as evidence for these claims. It is also proposed that future mind/brain research, subject to ethical constraints, will consist of a form of genetic engineering, whereby individual human genes belonging to the mind gene set are incorporated into the DNA of natural or artificial cells and the results observed. Mind gene theory is also used to resolve the current dispute between Dennett and Fodor on the role of evolution in cognition by claiming that both evolution and mentalism are required to explain the intentionality of cognitive states and processes. 
